                <div class="grid-img__content grid-img__content--right">
                    <h3 class="hd-3">Attention to Detail</h3>
                    <p>I added warnings to let you know when there are unsaved changes and an alert that alerts you if you try to leave the view (whether on purpose or accidentally) without saving. Some of these emails get pretty long also, so I have the iframe scroll to and highlight whatever section you’re editing as you update the content of the email. As a last touch, I added a dropdown that allows you to select any of the clients and preview the email as that client to view any customizations that would be made to the content. We even added the ability for the client to preview the email in one of our apps and approve it for their users before we send it!</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="grid-main u-margin--b-m">
            <div class="grid-main__gutter-l"></div>
            <div class="grid-main__content">
                <h3 class="hd-3">Admin Development</h3>
                <div class="columns">
                    <p>The next piece of this project was creating the admin to organize the templates into coordinated campaigns that we can send to clients. We have a pretty unique set of rules that control this, so I don’t want to divulge too much, but this system was at a place where it was hard to explain to anyone new joining the team, as it was a methodology that grew organically over many years as the business grew. The legacy system also did not report how the campaigns were synced with the third party system we use to send the emails.</p>

                    <p>The solution was to back and assess how the pieces of the system fit together and create a shared language for the team to understand and communicate it to one another and to future hires. I sat down the backend developer that was syncing this info with the party mailing provider to hash out what to call everything, used the [Breadboarding] methodology to rapidly work through UI options until we were satisfied. Then I build out the system of Vue components to power all the forms and view for creating campaigns, including controls to generate campaign sets from information such as client geographical data.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

